Tidy Data: Collapsing Languages Degree of Endangerment to Representing Country

Cleaning and tidy of data is essential before we can merge with other data sets to draw any insights between the original data set of Language Extinction with data sets that is grouped in regards of country, eg education statistics or country GDP statistics.

The Language Extinction data sets consist of languages that spans to multiple countries. Separately, in a specific country, there are multiple languages that is on endangered list.

For languages that span to multiple country, we use the supplied coordinates to identify the country origin and only use that as base. And for each country with multiple languages, we re-index the degree of endangerment for each language on country level using median of the contributed languages as the new index. The re-index of degree of endangerment of languages within a country to boundary of country level helps to normalize the different data sets that is based on country for insights in regards to country as boundary.

Using coordinates to identify single country as based reference

We first removed entry in the language extinction data set that do not have coordinate before we feed the data to function coords2location() to look up country code from the given coordinates. The removed entry only have 1 country assign to each language and we will merge back this entry after we found the country code.

We only use entries that have multiple countries stated in the original data set to overide the original country reference, and languages that only have single country will remain unchanged.

na.coord<-ext.lang.elevation %>% filter(is.na(Longitude)) %>% 
                                  mutate(Country.codes.alpha.3.coord=Country.codes.alpha.3)
ext.lang.elevation<-ext.lang.elevation %>% filter(!is.na(Longitude)) %>%
                      mutate(mult= Country.codes.alpha.3=="" | grepl(",", Country.codes.alpha.3),
                          Country.codes.alpha.3.coord=
                          ifelse(mult,as.character(
                            coords2location(data.frame(lng=Longitude, lat=Latitude))), 
                              Country.codes.alpha.3 ) ) %>% select(-mult)
#Correct country code SDS to SDN
sds.rec<-ext.lang.elevation %>% 
  filter(Country.codes.alpha.3.coord=="SDS") %>% 
  mutate(Country.codes.alpha.3.coord="SDN")
ext.lang.elevation<-rbind(ext.lang.elevation %>% filter(!(ID %in% sds.rec$ID)), 
                          sds.rec,
                          na.coord)

Re-index Degree of Endangerment for languages on country boundary

Languages are developed within communities and over the years migration happens which spread the language to nearby countries. However a country policy on education and socioeconomics may pay roles in language cultivation, therefore we normalize the language extinction level from per language level and aggregated up to per country level. Theres option to aggregate the level using average score or median. The summary of both mean and median on the index do not show significant difference, hence our approach will be using median as the Degree of Endangerment Index value ranging 1 to 5 ascending by severity.

ext.lang.elevation<-ext.lang.elevation %>% 
        mutate(DoE.num=as.numeric(factor(Degree.of.endangerment, 
                                         levels=c("Vulnerable", "Definitely endangered", 
                                         "Severely endangered", "Critically endangered",
                                         "Extinct"))))
country.DoE<-aggregate( DoE.num ~ Country.codes.alpha.3.coord, data=ext.lang.elevation,
                        function(x) { 
                          c(idx.med=median(x), idx.avg=round(mean(x),1), count=length(x))})
country.DoE <- data.frame(Country.codes=country.DoE$Country.codes.alpha.3.coord,
                       Degree.of.Endangerment.median=country.DoE$DoE.num[,1],
                       Degree.of.Endangerment.mean=country.DoE$DoE.num[,2],
                       Language.count=country.DoE$DoE.num[,3]) 
country.DoE<-cleanCountryName(country.DoE)
kable(summary(country.DoE[,-c(1,5)]))

Observations

It is interesting to see that country with high GDP like Germany, Belarus, Spain and Italy have a very low index of 1 or 2 (vulnerable or definately endangered) on 9, 3, 5 and 26 listed threaten languages respectively, and some country like Iraq, Nigeria, Ghana having high index > 4 (critically endangered or extinct). We will explore further with regards to the country statistic to show more insights.

Appendix

Function to lookup country code in ISO3 based on coordinates (latitude, longitude).

## Code from:http://stackoverflow.com/questions/21708488/get-country-and-continent-from-longitude-and-latitude-point-in-r
# The single argument to this function, points, is a data.frame in which:
#   - column 1 contains the longitude in degrees
#   - column 2 contains the latitude in degrees
coords2location = function(points)
{  
  require(sp)
  require(rworldmap)
  require(rworldxtra)
  countriesSP <- getMap(resolution='high')
  
  # converting points to a SpatialPoints object
  # setting CRS directly to that from rworldmap
  pointsSP = SpatialPoints(points, proj4string=CRS(proj4string(countriesSP)))  
  
  
  # use 'over' to get indices of the Polygons object containing each point 
  indices = over(pointsSP, countriesSP)
  
  #indices$continent   # returns the continent (6 continent model)
  #indices$REGION   # returns the continent (7 continent model)
  #indices$ADMIN  #returns country name
  #indices$ISO3 # returns the ISO3 code 
  indices$ISO3
}

Clean up some missing countries lookup from countrycode library:

cleanCountryName<-function(country.df) {
  require(dplyr)
  require(countrycode)
  country.df<-country.DoE %>% 
    mutate(Country.name=countrycode(country.DoE$Country.codes, "iso3c", "country.name", warn=F))
  country.df[country.DoE$Country.codes=="ANG", "Country.name"] = "Angola"
  country.df[country.DoE$Country.codes=="ZAI", "Country.name"] = "Democratic Republic of the Congo"
  country.df
}

Map properties

getMapGepProp<-function(){
  list(
    showframe = T,
    showocean = T,
    #oceancolor = 'rgb(28,107,160)',
    oceancolor = 'rgb(222,243,246)',
    projection = list(
      type = 'natural earth',  #"natural earth", equirectangular, orthographic
      rotation = list(
        lon = 10,
        lat = 10)
    ),
    lonaxis =  list(
      showgrid = F,
      gridcolor = 'rgb(102, 102, 102)'
    ),
    lataxis = list(
      showgrid = F,
      gridcolor = 'rgb(102, 102, 102)'
    )
  )
}
plotMap<-function(image=F) {
  require(plotly)
  p<-plot_geo(locations=country.DoE$Country.code, 
           marker = list(colorbar = list(title = 'Country Median DoE')),
           colorscale="YlOrRd",
           text=paste(country.DoE$Country.name, country.DoE$Language.count, sep = "-"),
           z=country.DoE$Degree.of.Endangerment.median) %>%
    layout(
      showlegend = T, geo = getMapGepProp(),
      title = 'World Language Degree of Endangerment Scale by Country<br>(Click and drag to rotate)'
    )
  if(image) { 
    plotly_IMAGE(p, format = "png", out_file = "img/worldmap.png")
  } else {
    p
  }
}
plotMapCount<-function(image=F) {
  require(plotly)
  p<-plot_geo(locations=country.DoE$Country.code, 
           marker = list(colorbar = list(title = 'Language Count')),
           colorscale="YlOrRd",
           text=paste(country.DoE$Country.name, country.DoE$Degree.of.Endangerment.median, sep = "-"),
           z=country.DoE$Language.count) %>%
    layout(
      showlegend = T, geo = getMapGepProp(),
      title = 'World Endangered Language Count by Country<br>(Click and drag to rotate)'
    )
  if(image) { 
    plotly_IMAGE(p, format = "png", out_file = "img/worldmap.png")
  } else {
    p
  }
}
